        <h2 id="examples">Real mega-influencer campaign examples</h2>
        <p>Two types of outcomes illustrate the range:</p>

        <h3>1. Sportswear brand x athlete (8M followers)</h3>
        <p>A sportswear brand partnered with an athlete influencer for a 3-post deal worth $150,000. The campaign reached 3.2 million people in 24 hours and drove a 400% spike in brand search volume in the week following publication. Direct purchases from the posts were minimal — the brand correctly measured it as an awareness and search lift play.</p>

        <h3>2. Tech company YouTube integration (5M subscribers)</h3>
        <p>A SaaS company paid $250,000 for a 90-second YouTube integration on a tech creator's channel. The video drove 200,000 website visits over 7 days and 8,000 free trial signups — a $31.25 cost per trial. For a $200/year subscription product, that unit economics made sense. For a $29/month product, it would not have.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Mega-influencer vs. micro-influencer — which to use</h2>
        <p>The choice isn't about which is "better." It's about matching the tool to the campaign objective.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use a mega-influencer when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Campaign goal is brand awareness or launch reach</li>
              <li>You need to reach 1M+ people in a single window</li>
              <li>Cultural relevance or celebrity association is the message</li>
              <li>Budget allows $50K+ per activation</li>
              <li>You're entering a new market where credibility is built by association</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use micro or nano-influencers when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Campaign goal is conversions, not reach</li>
              <li>Product has a specific niche audience</li>
              <li>You need authentic community trust</li>
              <li>Budget is under $20,000 total</li>
              <li>You want measurable ROI on direct sales</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for mega-influencer campaigns</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Define the goal before the creator.</strong> "Awareness" is not a goal. "Drive 2 million impressions and a 20% lift in branded search in 30 days" is a goal. Work backwards from the metric to the creator.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit engagement quality, not just follower count.</strong> Fake followers are common at this tier. Check comment quality, engagement rate history, and audience authenticity using tools like HypeAuditor or Modash.</li>
          <li><strong>Negotiate usage rights upfront.</strong> Without usage rights, you can't run the creator's content as paid ads — which is often where the real ROI lives. Negotiate these before signing.</li>
          <li><strong>Build in approval rounds.</strong> Mega-influencer content goes out to millions of people. Require 48-72 hour approval windows before publication. A brand-safety mishap on this scale is public.</li>
          <li><strong>Measure brand search lift, not just last-click.</strong> Mega-influencer campaigns move brand search volume 200-400% in the post period. If you're only looking at UTM clicks, you're missing most of the value.</li>
          <li><strong>Pair with retargeting.</strong> People who see the mega-influencer post and don't convert immediately are still warm. Run retargeting ads to audiences who engaged with the content to capture bottom-funnel intent.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — using reach as a proxy for results</div>
          <p>A campaign that reaches 5 million people and drives zero searches, zero traffic, and zero branded interest was not successful because of its reach number. Always track downstream signals: brand search volume, direct traffic spikes, and social mention volume — not just impressions.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common mega-influencer mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Picking by follower count alone</strong> — a creator with 5M disengaged followers is worth less than one with 1.5M active community members. Engagement rate matters more than raw numbers.</li>
          <li><strong>No usage rights in the contract</strong> — leaving the creator's high-quality content unused in paid media is a significant missed opportunity.</li>
          <li><strong>No exclusivity clause</strong> — a creator who posts for your competitor 2 weeks later makes your campaign look less credible.</li>
          <li><strong>Measuring ROI on last-click</strong> — mega-influencer value is predominantly awareness and upper-funnel. Attributing it to direct sales conversions will always make it look bad.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping the creative brief</strong> — leaving too much to the creator without guardrails can result in content that doesn't connect the product to its value proposition clearly.</li>
        </ul>

